'''Olympias''' (in [[Greek language|Greek]] Ὀλυμπιάς, {{IPA-el|olympiás|pron}}; lived 3rd century BC) was daughter of [[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus]], king of [[Epirus]] from his first wife [[Antigone of Epirus|Antigone]]. She was the wife of her own paternal half-brother [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander II]]. After his death she assumed the regency of the kingdom on behalf of her two sons, [[Pyrrhus II of Epirus|Pyrrhus II]] and [[Ptolemy of Epirus|Ptolemy]]; and in order to strengthen herself against the [[Aetolian League]] she gave before 239 BC her daughter [[Phthia of Macedonia|Phthia]] in marriage to [[Demetrius II of Macedon|Demetrius II]], king of [[Macedon]]ia. By this alliance she secured herself in the possession of the sovereignty, which she continued to administer till her sons were grown up to manhood, when she resigned it into the hands of Pyrrhus II. But the deaths of that prince and his brother Ptolemy followed in quick succession, and Olympias herself died of grief for her double loss.{{r|just_28.3}} Such is [[Junianus Justinus|Justin]]'s statement: according to another account Olympias had poisoned a [[Lefkada|Leucadian]] damsel named Tigris, to whom her son Pyrrhus was attached, and was herself poisoned by him in revenge.{{r|ath_13_phot}}

