'''Peter Tangvald''' (born '''Per Tangvald''', 27 September 1924, died 22 June 1991) was a Norwegian sailor and adventurer. Known as one of the early deep-sea cruising pioneers and for his 1966 book ''Sea Gypsy'', he reached notoriety after two of his seven wives had been lost at sea.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wavetrain.net/lit-bits/713-sea-gypsy-early-adventures-of-peter-tangvald|title=SEA GYPSY: Early Adventures of Peter Tangvald|last=Doane|first=Charles|website=www.wavetrain.net|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://bonairereporter.com/news/2001issues/07-18-01/page9.htm|title=Sailor Peter Tangvald Remembered|last=|first=|date=2001-07-18|website=bonairereporter.com|publisher=Bonaire Reporter|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=At Any Cost: Love, Life & Death at Sea: An Autobiography|last=Tangvald|first=Peter|publisher=Cruising Guide Publications|year=1991|isbn=0944428096|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> He himself drowned, along with his daughter Carmen, when his engineless yacht was wrecked in [[Bonaire]] in 1991.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> His son Thomas escaped the accident, but suffered a similar fate when his own yacht was lost at sea years later, in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wavetrain.net/news-a-views/585-thomas-tangvald-declared-lost-at-sea|title=THOMAS TANGVALD: Declared Lost At Sea|last=Doane|first=Charles|date=2014-05-09|website=www.wavetrain.net|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sailmagazine.com/cruising/profiles-cruising/remembering-thomas-tangvald/|title=Remembering Thomas Tangvald - Sail Magazine|date=2016-03-29|newspaper=Sail Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>

